<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-128-343 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 928 306</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  June 17 1991 v5 n17 p30(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Flopticals make light of data storage, retrieval; reads 20M on3.5-inch floppy.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Danca, Richard A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Insite Peripherals has created a new disk media it is calling thefloptical disk that can store 20Mbytes of data on a 3.5-inchfloppy disk.andP;  Floptical disks use an optical beam to preciselyposition a magnetic read/write head, enabling much higher storagedensities.andP;  The 20Mbyte version will be available by the end ofsummer 1991 at a price of between $450 and $800 for the drive and$20 to $25 for the disk.andP;  Insite expects prices to falldrastically as demand increases.andP;  The firm also expects tointroduce disks that can handle 40- and 80Mbytes of data in thenear future.andP;  Floptical disks use the standard small computersystem interface (SCSI) and can read and write data ontotraditional 3.5-inch floppies without modification.andP;  Insite hasformed the Floptical Technology Alliance with Iomega, HitachiMaxell Ltd and 3M Corp.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Insite Peripherals Inc. (Innovations).andO;Topic:     High-Density StorageFloppy DiskData CompressionNew TechniqueOptical DisksStorage MediaSmall Computer Systems InterfaceMagnetic Disks3.5&quot; Disk.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Diagram of floptical disk technology. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>